## Capture etiquette

The graph rewards **sharp, specific, story-bearing** entries and **punishes
vagueness**. A few rules that hold across all files:

- **Specific beats general.** "Customer p95 latency exceeded 14s during
Black Friday traffic spike" beats "the site was slow once".
- **Stories beat opinions.** Capture the situation, the choice, the
outcome. Avoid bare assertions.
- **Cross-link generously.** Use `[[file-name]]` syntax to wire entries
together. The graph is more than the sum of its files.
- **Append-only.** Never delete an entry that captured a real learning,
even if conditions change. Mark superseded entries and link to their
replacement.
- **Date everything.** Future readers (including you) need to know when
this was true.
- **Sanitize secrets, sanitize people.** No credentials, no salaries,
no performance opinions about named individuals.

---

## When NOT to capture

The graph degrades when it accumulates noise. Skip capturing when:

- The fact is already true in code (e.g., the list of API endpoints —
read the code).
- The "learning" has no forward-looking reflex (just "stuff happened").
- The detail is one-off and won't recur.
- The entry is a vent, not a finding.

Empty space in a file is honest. Fake entries to "look prepared" are
worse than empty — they dilute the signal Claude reads.

