## Capture model — just-in-time, not a separate ritual

The graph stays current through **capture inside the normal
conversation flow**, not via a scheduled daily ritual. An earlier
"15-minute daily ritual" framing was overstated and was retired
2025-10-15 — it implied a recurring chore the framework never actually
required.

How it actually works:

1. **During regular work — just-in-time.** When Claude detects a
   capture trigger (new domain term, new business rule, vendor choice,
   dev override, plan rejection, incident, anti-pattern), it proposes
   a structured entry inline. The dev confirms / refines / declines
   in 5-30 seconds. Captures happen inside the existing dialogue, not
   as a separate sit-down.

2. **One-time bootstrap (1-3 hours).** When adopting the framework on
   an existing project, backfill the categories in the bootstrap order
   below. This is the only sit-down session required, and only once
   per project.

3. **Optional quarterly review (15-30 minutes).** Re-read the graph
   end-to-end. Mark obsolete entries `Status: superseded`. Add
   cross-links you've noticed since the last review. Quarterly is
   recommended but not load-bearing.

Real continuous cost is near-zero overhead. The graph decays only if
capture triggers are routinely ignored — not because a daily ritual
was skipped.

---

## Bootstrap order (for empty projects)

When starting from a fresh `/rsct-setup` install, the templates land
empty. Fill them in this order — easiest to hardest:

1. `business-glossary.md` — domain terms you already say out loud.
2. `vendor-relationships.md` — your stack is already known.
3. `team-capabilities.md` — current snapshot of skills + capacity.
4. `workflow-rituals.md` — your existing PR/deploy flow.
5. `business-rules.md` — invariants you've stated to customers or
auditors.
6. `stakeholder-map.md` — current approval chain.
7. `infrastructure.md` (at `documentation/infrastructure.md`) — current
deployed services.
8. `cost-constraints.md` — top line items in your bill.
9. `incident-log.md` — backfill the last 3-5 significant incidents.
10. `anti-decisions.md` — the hardest one; requires digging through PRs,
retros, archived branches.
11. `domain-edge-cases.md` — emerges over time as bugs are fixed.

Don't try to fill everything in one sitting. 1-2 entries per file is a
respectable bootstrap; the rest grows organically through the capture
ritual.
